CHAPTER XIV WHEN SHALL THESE THREE MEET AGAIN ? CHRISTMAS EVE in Cloisterham . 
To these , the striking of the Cathedral clock , and the cawing of the rooks from the Cathedral tower , are like voices of their nursery time . 
Lavish profusion is in the shops particularly in the articles of currants , raisins , spices , candied peel , and moist sugar . 
Public amusements are not wanting . 
In short , Cloisterham is up and doing though from this description the High School and Miss Twinkleton's are to be excluded . 
and only the handmaidens flutter occasionally in the windows of the latter . 
